BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260326T210000Z
DTEND:20260326T220000Z
LOCATION:Asian Culture Center (807 E 10th street\, Bloomington\, IN)
SUMMARY:ACC Book Club features "To Save and Destroy" by Viet Nguyen
DESCRIPTION:What does it mean to be&#160\;an "other"? How can writing shi
 ft the boundaries between insider and outsider for both author and audien
 ce? All are welcome to join the ACC in discussing these questions over di
 nner through Viet Thanh Nguyen's essay collection&#160\;To Save and&#160\
 ;to Destroy: Writing as an Other. Originally delivered as the Norton Lect
 ure series at Harvard in 2023-24\, the six chapters span Nguyen's reflect
 ions on war\, solidarity\, and power\, drawing from sources ranging from 
 classics of American literature to Nguyen's own lived experience as a ref
 ugee. Digital copies of the eBook are&#160\;freely available to access th
 rough IU Libraries\, so all attendees are welcome to read ahead! Pizza wi
 ll be served at each meeting.&#160\;For more information\, please reach o
 ut to ACC volunteer and book club moderator Cheryl Nong\, PhD student in 
 social psychology\, at&#160\;acc@iu.edu. The next book club meeting is on
  March 26\, 2026.&#160\;&#160\;All Indiana University events\, groups\, a
 ctivities\, and&#160\;educational\, cultural\, and historical observances
  welcome all IU students and other members of the Indiana University comm
 unity.For more information\, view this event in BeInvolved (https://beinv
 olved.indiana.edu/event/11950464).
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><span data-contrast="none">What does it m
 ean to be&#160\;an "other"? How can writing shift the boundaries between 
 insider and outsider for both author and audience? All are welcome to joi
 n the ACC in discussing these questions over dinner through Viet Thanh Ng
 uyen's essay collection&#160\;</span><em><span data-contrast="none">To Sa
 ve and&#160\;to Destroy: Writing as an Other</span></em><span data-contra
 st="none">. Originally delivered as the Norton Lecture series at Harvard 
 in 2023-24\, the six chapters span Nguyen's reflections on war\, solidari
 ty\, and power\, drawing from sources ranging from classics of American l
 iterature to Nguyen's own lived experience as a refugee. Digital copies o
 f the eBook are&#160\;</span><a href="http://proxyiub.uits.iu.edu/login?u
 rl=https://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&amp\;scope=site&am
 p\;db=nlebk&amp\;db=nlabk&amp\;AN=4150320"><span data-contrast="none">fre
 ely available to access through IU Libraries</span></a><span data-contras
 t="none">\, so all attendees are welcome to read ahead! Pizza will be ser
 ved at each meeting.</span><span data-ccp-props="{&quot\;134233117&quot\;
 :false\,&quot\;134233118&quot\;:false\,&quot\;335557856&quot\;:16777215\,
 &quot\;335559738&quot\;:0\,&quot\;335559739&quot\;:0}">&#160\;</span></p>
 <br /><p><span data-contrast="none">For more information\, please reach o
 ut to ACC volunteer and book club moderator Cheryl Nong\, PhD student in 
 social psychology\, at&#160\;</span><a href="mailto:acc@indiana.edu"><spa
 n data-contrast="none">acc@iu.edu</span></a><span data-contrast="none">. 
 The next book club meeting is on March 26\, 2026.&#160\;</span><span data
 -ccp-props="{&quot\;134233117&quot\;:false\,&quot\;134233118&quot\;:false
 \,&quot\;335557856&quot\;:16777215\,&quot\;335559738&quot\;:0\,&quot\;335
